Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

by Ayodeji Arowolo¶

Introduction¶

 The data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. The dataset primarily consists of data on the borrower's and the loan performance information.

Assessing and Cleaning the Data to be ready for Exploratory Data Analysis.¶

To assess and clean the data, I will perform the following steps.

  1. Decide on the columns that I will use for the analysis.
  2. Subset the columns from the original data that I will use.
  3. Drop any duplicated rows
  4. Subset for rows with a ProsperRating value
  5. Fill missing values
  6. Change Datatypes

Deciding on the columns¶

##Obtaining time,day, month and year from the ListingCreationDate column
loan_df['month'] = loan_df.ListingCreationDate.apply(lambda x: x.split("-")[1]).astype(str)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset (loan_df) now has 84,853 entries and 19 columns across the loan and borrowers information. There are numeric and qualitative data in the dataset. The prosperrating, BorrowerAPR, loan amount are some of the very important columns in the data.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main interest in my dataset is to find out what features can be used to predict the BorrowerAPR appropriately. How other features like the Occupation, Debttoincome ratio relate with other variables and affect the BoorowerAPR

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Having worked in the financial sector for several years, I know that a number of factors will affect BorrowerAPR like the following:

  1. The Occupation and debttoincomeratio largely affects the risk and ease with which financial institutions avails loans, which should directly impact the APR
  2. The loan amount should also affect the APR, as a higher loan amount should ordinarily mean a lower interest rate and APR
  3. Being a homeowner should also affect APR as it means the borrower has a reasonable collateral for the loan

def ordered_countploting(x,y):
    """this function will be used to create bar charts on loan_df with a defined order"""
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    plt.figure(figsize=[10,6])
    return sb.countplot(data = loan_df, x=x,color = base_color, order = y)

def countploting(x):
    """this function will be used to create bar charts on loan_df with a defined order"""
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    plt.figure(figsize=[10,6])
    return sb.countplot(data = loan_df, x=x,color = base_color)

The borrower rates correlates negatively with loan amount. The higher the loan amount, the lower the rates. It also means that borrowers who are employed or work full-time can access higher amounts and would most likely get lower rates compared to other borrowers.

The Prosper rating also has a high impact on borrower rates, the higher the prosper rating, the lower the rates applicable to the borrower

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In the multivariate exploration of data, I observed that prosper rating and employment status affect loan amount and rate. Borrower Rates decrease across all employment status, as the prosper rating for the borrower increases. However, as the employement status improves, with a higher prosper rating, the general trend where loan amount varies inversely with borrower rate changes. Instead, it becomes the higher the amount, there is a higher or near constant rate. The trend above does not appear to apply for part-time employees. They generally get a higher or near constant rate as the loan amount increases.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I observed that the borrower rate for home owners and non home owners decreased from 2011.

In conclusion, I was able to explore the data with univariate, bivariate and multivariate plots.

The most important insights I obtained during the analysis include the following:

  • Regardless of other features, loan amount generally varies inversely with borrower rate
  • Being a house owner improves the borrower's rate
  • The higher one's stated income, the higher the loan amount they can borrow.
  • Employee status affects the loan amount. The better the degree of a borrower's employment, the higher the loan amount they can borrow.
